Q. What is the difference between final, finalize(), finally() ?




-> Java provied 5 keywords to handle exceptions

                                        1.try
                                        2.catch
                                        3.finally
                                        4.throws
                                        5.throw

=====
try 
=====
-> It is used to keep risky code
syntax: 
           try {
                 //stmt
                  }


Note :  we can not write only try block. try block required catch or finally(it can have both also).

try-catch----> valid combiantion
try-finally---> vaild combiantion
try-catch-finally--> valid combination
only try block --> invalid

=======
catch
=======

=> catch block is used to catch the exception which occured in try block.
=> To write catch block , try block is mandatory.

syntax:  
                        try {
                              //logic
                        }catch(Exception e){
                       //logic to catch exception info
                        }
Note: If exception occured in try block then only catch block will execute otherwise catch block will not execute 

Example: 

package in.psa.userDemo;

public class Demo {

	
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		
		
		System.out.println("main () method started...");
		
		
		try{
		
			System.out.println("try block start....");
			
			int x =10 /0 ;
			
			String s = null;
		    s.length();
		    
		    System.out.println("try block end....");
		
		} catch(NullPointerException e) {
			System.out.println("in catch block..");
			e.printStackTrace();
			
		} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
			
			System.out.println("in catch block...");
			e.printStackTrace();
		}
		
		System.out.println("welcome to java......");
		
		System.out.println("main() method ended....... This is called graceful termination");
	}
}


Note: we can attach multiple catch {} block with a single try {} and order should be child to parent. But this is not a recommended approach.
       let's do recommended approach--->

package in.psa.userDemo;

public class Demo {

	
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		
		
		System.out.println("main () method started...");
		
		
